{"id":"0912.1030","submitter":"Marla Slusky","authors":"Marla Slusky","title":"Zeros of 2 by 2 Matrix Polynomials","comments":"14 Pages. Research done at an REU at Rutgers Universtiy in 2006 under\n  Robert Wilson","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Consider the $n$th degree polynomial equation,\n$X^n+A_{n-1}X^{n-1}+...+A_1X+A_0=0$ over the ring of 2 by 2 complex matrices.\nIf this equation has more than ${2n \\choose 2}$ solutions, then it has\ninfinitely many solutions. We show here that for any $n,m \\in\\N$ such that\n$m\\leq{2n \\choose 2}$, there exists an $n$th degree polynomial equation with\nexactly $m$ solutions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 5 Dec 2009 15:58:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-12-08"}
